n $X_i(n)=f_i({\\Upsilon }_n)$, where ${\\Upsilon }_n$ is a Markov chain\nsatisfying the Doeblin condition considered as a stationary process with\nrespect to its invariant measure. Moreover, our relaxed mixing conditions yield\napplications to other types of dynamical systems and Markov processes, for\ninstance, where a spectral gap can be established. The continuous time version\nholds true when, for instance, $X_i(t)=f_i(\\xi_t)$, where $\\xi_t$ is a\nnondegenerate continuous time Markov chain with a finite state space or a\nnondegenerate diffusion on a compact manifold. A partial motivation for such\nlimit theorems is due to a series of papers dealing with nonconventional\nergodic averages.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 10 Dec 2010 10:27:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 31 Dec 2011 12:05:10 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 23 Jan 2012 09:15:56 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 25 Feb 2014 14:31:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-02-26"}
